        "text": "Working Hours\n\nThe standard work week is eight hours a day or 48 hours per week. This is reduced to seven hours a day or 42 hours per week for night shift workers.\n\nMinimum Wage\n\nNIO 4,414.91 to 9,880.17 per month, depending on the sector.\n\nEmployee Tax\n\nAnnual income\n\nTax rate\n\nUp to NIO 100,000\n\n0%\n\nNIO 100,001 - 200,000\n\n15%\n\nNIO 200,001 – 350,000\n\n20%\n\nNIO 350,001 - 500,000\n\n25%\n\nMore than NIO 500,001\n\n30%\n\nPension & disability contribution\n\n4.75%\n\nHealth insurance contribution\n\n2.25%\n\nBonuses\n\nEmployees are entitled to an additional monthly salary, at the end of each year as a Christmas bonus.\n\nEmployment contracts in Nicaragua can be written or oral, though oral contracts are only allowed for agricultural, housekeeping, or temporary work of no more than ten days.\n\nWritten contracts should be drafted in Spanish and signed by both parties. They should include:\n\nEmployee and employer details\n\nJob title and responsibilities\n\nWorkplace\n\nSalary\n\nWorking hours\n\nContract length (if applicable)\n\nDate and location of contract signing.\n\nBoth indefinite and fixed-term contracts are permitted in Nicaragua.\n\nTermination Process\n\nThere are several grounds for contract termination in Nicaragua:\n\nIncapacity to work\n\nMutual consent\n\nImprisonment or court order\n\nAct of God\n\nRetirement\n\nNotice may be required in some cases, but it’s unclear how much notice is required from the employer. Employees must give at least 15 days’ notice of their resignation.\n\nWrongful termination may lead to reinstatement, plus compensation.\n\nSeverance Pay\n\nSeverance is payable for all types of termination. Employees are entitled to holiday pay and the 13th month salary. If compensation is due, it is paid at a rate of one month’s salary per year of service up to three years, plus 20 days’ wages per subsequent year of service."
